'''Diagnostic Drawing Series'''

The Diagnostic Drawing Series (DDS) is a three-picture art interview developed in 1982 by art therapists Barry M. Cohen and Barbara Lesowitz. The DDS Rating Guide (Cohen, 1986/1994) provides clearly defined and illustrated criteria that highlight the structure, not the content, of the drawings.  The DDS was the first [[art therapy]] assessment for adults to be systematically correlated with the nomenclature of the [[Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders]] (DSM) through research.  More than 50 DDS studies have been completed thus far, including tests of reliability and validity (DDS Resource List, Mills, 2006).  

The above was excerpted with permission from Report on the Diagnostic Drawing Series, October 2000 (Cohen & Mills).

